2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Niels, Lars, Nels, Per, Anders, Holger, Jorgen, Thor, Bjorn, Helmer, Alf.","Norwegian, Danish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Anders</i>, a vernacular form of   Andreas  . Compare   Anderson   1.","Americanized form of Norwegian, North German, and very rare Danish patronymic <b>Anderssen</b>, a cognate of 1 above. Compare   Andersson   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Andreas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Heinz, Otto, Beate, Bernd, Ernst, Ilse, Kurt.","German and English: from the New Testament Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, which gave rise to   Andrew   in English and vernacular derivatives in almost every other European language. Etymologically, it is from Greek <i>andreios</i> ‘manly’, an adjective derivative of <i>anēr</i> (genitive <i>andros</i>) ‘man, male’. This is a Greek translation of an unknown Aramaic original; it was the name of the first of Christ's disciples, the patron saint of both Scotland and Russia. The Scottish surname   Anderson   is far more common than its Russian equivalent, <b>Andreev</b>. The personal name was popular throughout Europe in various vernacular forms (including Italian <i>Andrea</i>, French <i>André</i>, Spanish <i>Andrés</i>, Scottish, North German, and Scandinavian <i>Anders</i>, Dutch <i>Andries</i>, Hungarian <i>András</i>, Czech <i>Ondřej</i>, Polish <i>Andrzej</i> and <i>Jędrzej</i>, and Russian <i>Andrey</i>).","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Andrejaš</b>: from an old vernacular form of the personal name <i>Andraž</i> (from Latin <i>Andreas</i>), which is a variant of <i>Andrej</i>; see   Andrew  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Ann Andersen was born about 1600, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Hutchins in 1600, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1620, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt. 1600–Aft. 1620":"umbes 1600–pärast 1620","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1584–1648":"1584–1648","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","Abt. 1600":"umbes 1600","Aft. 1620":"pärast 1620","1584":"1584","1648":"1648","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt. 1600–Aft. 1620":"noin 1600–1620 jälkeen","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1584–1648":"1584–1648","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","Abt. 1600":"noin 1600","Aft. 1620":"1620 jälkeen","1584":"1584","1648":"1648","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt. 1600–Aft. 1620":"environ 1600–après 1620","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1584–1648":"1584–1648","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","Abt. 1600":"environ 1600","Aft. 1620":"après 1620","1584":"1584","1648":"1648","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lady Ann Andersen est née environ 1600, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Sir Hutchins en 1600, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 